{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778707036,"nonce":"lzQclEcqanad7Xu8f/Kb3fte9Lc=","title":"RunPod direct-image pulls hit Docker Hub anonymous rate limit","message":"When creating a RunPod pod with `--image runpod/pytorch:1.0.3-cu1281-torch290-ubuntu2204` (direct Docker Hub reference), the pod fails to boot. Logs surface:\n\n  error creating container: failed to pull image: toomanyrequests: You have reached your unauthenticated pull rate limit.\n\nThe pod-get `.ssh` field stays at `error: pod not ready` indefinitely; `uptimeSeconds: 0`. Without surfaced container logs, this looks identical to a slow-booting pod — an agent could waste an hour polling.\n\n**Workaround (validated this session):** create the pod via `--template-id runpod-torch-v280` instead of `--image`. RunPod templates pull from RunPod's internal registry, bypassing Docker Hub. The v280 template's image (`runpod/pytorch:1.0.2-cu1281-torch280-ubuntu2404`) is the validated 5090 image per rlrmp CLAUDE.md §3.\n\n**Prevention proposal — file dotfiles issue against CLAUDE.md RunPod runbook (rlrmp §3/§4a):**\n1. Prefer `--template-id` over raw `--image` for standard pytorch-CUDA images.\n2. Add a diagnostic step: if SSH not ready after ~3 min, fetch container logs via `runpodctl pod logs` (or equivalent) before continuing to poll, to surface boot failures like this one.\n3. Note that anonymous Docker Hub pulls are rate-limited per shared RunPod node IP, not per-user — so a fresh deploy on a hot node can fail even when the same image worked yesterday.\n\nSurfaced from rlrmp `b399efc` matrix-run session 2026-05-13.","files":null}]}